ering all emerging tobacco products and [[shisha]] comes into effect.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/full-ban-shisha-emerging-tobacco-products-spore-aug-1 | title= Full ban on shisha, emerging tobacco products in S'pore from Aug 1 | publisher= Todayonline | accessdate= 5 July 2019 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190705043703/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/full-ban-shisha-emerging-tobacco-products-spore-aug-1 | archive-date= 5 July 2019 | date= 28 July 2016 | url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lai |first1=Linette |title=MOH bans new forms of tobacco products from Dec 15, 2015 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/moh-bans-new-forms-of-tobacco-products-from-dec-15-2015 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=30 March 2020 |date=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n*5\u201321 August \u2013 25 athletes from [[Singapore at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Singapore]] compete at the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]. The team produced a single medal: (on 12 August Brazil time/13 August Singapore time) swimmer [[Joseph Schooling]] beat American [[Michael Phelps]] (then the [[list of multiple Olympic medalists|most decorated Olympian of all time]]) in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]] to win Singapore's first ever Olympic gold medal and set an Olympic record.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Low|first1=Lin Fhoong|title=Rio wrap-up: Schooling saves the day for Team Singapore|url=http://www.todayonline.com/sports/schooling-saves-day-team-singapore|work=[[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]]|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Graham|first1=Chris|title='I'm ready to retire,' Michael Phelps says as American finishes second in three-way tie behind Singapore's Joseph Schooling|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/12/michael-phelps-goes-for-gold-rio-olympics-100m-butterfly-live/|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Phelps suffers shock defeat by Schooling, Singapore's first Olympic gold medallist |publisher=RIO 2016 Official website |date=12 August 2016 |url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/news/rio-2016-olympic-games-schooling-phelps-usa-singapore-gold-medal-100m-butterfly |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826191932/https://www.rio2016.com/en/news/rio-2016-olympic-games-schooling-phelps-usa-singapore-gold-medal-100m-butterfly |archivedate=26 August 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Schooling wins gold: Live Blog|url=http://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/2016/08/olympics-blog/index.html|publisher=[[The Straits Times]]|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n*5 August \u2013 Indonesian police foils a rocket plot on [[Marina Bay, Singapore|Marina Bay]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Arshad |first1=Arlina |last2=Lee |first2=Seok Hwai |title=Indonesian police foil rocket attack plot on Marina Bay; Singapore steps up security |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/indonesian-police-arrest-six-batam-militants |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=2 July 2019 |date=5 August 2016}}</ref>\n*6 August \u2013 ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Go]]'', a record-setting [[augmented reality]] game, is officially released in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pokemon Go launches in Singapore |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/pokemon-go-launches-in/2953980.html |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=6 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806110343/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/pokemon-go-launches-in/2953980.html |archive-date=6 August 2016 |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Swatman|first1=Rachel|title=Pok\u00e9mon Go catches five new world records|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2016/8/pokemon-go-catches-five-world-records-439327|publisher=[[Guinness World Records]]|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n*15 August \u2013 The Administration of Justice (Protection) Act is passed to deal with cases of [[Offence of scandalizing the court in Singapore|contempt of court]] more effectively.<ref>{{cite web|title=Contempt of court Bill passed after seven-hour debate|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/contempt-of-court-bill-passed-after-seven-hour-debate|publisher=The Straits Times|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref> \n*21 August \u2013 A health scare occurs during the [[National Day Rally]] speech, which is resolved an hour later.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore PM Lee Hsien Loong returns to finish speech at NDR 2016 after being taken ill |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-pm-lee-hsien-loong-returns-to-finish-speech-at-ndr-201-7884264 |website=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=5 June 2019 |date=21 August 2016}}</ref>\n*22 August \u2013 Former [[President of Singapore|President]], [[S.R. Nathan]] (the nation's sixth and longest-serving at the time) dies at the age of 92, after suffering a [[stroke]] three weeks prior.<ref name=\"SRN\">{{cite web | access-date=29 September 2019 | first1=Zi Liang | last1=Chong | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/former-president-sr-nathan-dies-aged-92 | title=Former president S R Nathan dies, aged 92 | date=22 August 2016 | website=The Straits Times}}</ref> On 25 August, over 20,000 paid their respects when he was [[lying in state]] at [[Parliament House, Singapore]]. On 26 August, Nathan was accorded a [[state funeral]] and was cremated at [[Mandai Crematorium]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tham|first1=Yuen-C|title=Thousands say goodbye to S R Nathan|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/politics/thousands-say-goodbye-to-s-r-nathan|publisher=[[The Straits Times]]|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=State Funeral held for former President S R Nathan|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/as-it-happens-state/3075094.html|publisher=[[Channel News Asia]]}}</ref>\n*25 August \u2013 [[NuTonomy]] launches the world's first [[autonomous car|driverless]] taxi trials in [[one-north]].<ref>{{cite web |title=World's first driverless taxi trial kicks off in Singapore |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/worlds-first-driverless-taxi-trial-kicks-off-in-singapore |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n*26 August \u2013 During the [[2016 Southeast Asian haze]] caused by Indonesia, Singapore's 24-hour Pollutant Standards Index (PSI) entered the 'unhealthy' range of above 100, while its 3-hour PSI reached 215.<ref>{{cite web|title=The haze is back across South East Asia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37192800|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Md Noh|first1=Nurulnadiah|last2=Tan|first2=Audrey|title=Haze update: PSI for next 24 hours forecast to be in unhealthy range, says NEA|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/environment/haze-back-in-singapore-24-hour-psi-reaches-moderate-level|publisher=[[The Straits Times]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref>\n*27\u201331 August \u2013 Over five days, the first 115 cases of locally transmitted Zika virus infection in Singapore are confirmed; 110 from the combined area of Aljunied Crescent, Kallang Way, Paya Lebar Way and Sims Drive. The remaining live at various areas: Bedok North Avenue 3, Joo Seng Road, and Punggol Way.<ref>{{cite web|title=First case of locally-transmitted Zika virus infection reported in Singapore: MOH, NEA|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/first-case-of-locally/3078974.html|publisher=[[Channel News Asia]]|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Local Zika cases in Singapore jump to 115; first pregnant woman diagnosed|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/local-zika-cases-in/3089076.html|publisher=[[Channel News Asia]]|accessdate=2 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n*4 September \u2013 Services 3, 34, 43/43M, 62, 82, 83, 84, 85, 118, 119, 136, 382 & 386 handed over to [[Go-Ahead Singapore]].\n*7\u201318 September \u2013 13 athletes from [[Singapore at the 2016 Summer Paralympics|Singapore]] compete in six sports (archery, athletics, [[boccia]], [[Para-equestrian|equestrian]], swimming, and sailing) at the [[2016 Summer Paralympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Team Singapore head for the Rio Paralympics|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/sport/team-singapore-head-for-the-rio-paralympics|work=[[The Straits Times]]|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> On 10 September, swimmer [[Yip Pin Xiu]] won a gold medal in the 100m backstroke, S2 finals with a world record of 2:07.09, with an additional world record for the 59.38 split for the first 50m of the race.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yip Pin Xiu sets two world records in gold-medal swim at Paralympics|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/yip-pin-xiu-sets-two-world-records-gold-medal-swim-paralympics|work=[[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]]|date=10 September 2016|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref> Yip won another gold medal on 16 September in the 50m backstroke, S2 finals with a time of 1:00.33, becoming the first Singaporean to win multiple gold medals at the Paralympics.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chew |first1=Joan |title=Paralympics: Yip Pin Xiu wins 2nd gold at Rio Games, says 'words cannot describe how I feel now' |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/sport/paralympics-history-maker-yip-pin-xiu-wins-gold-in-womens-50m-backstroke-s2-second-title-of |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=8 December 2019 |date=16 September 2016}}</ref> On 12 September, swimmer [[Theresa Goh]] won a bronze medal in the SB4 100m breaststroke final, with a time of 1:55.55.<ref name=16Para100mbreastFinals>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/sport/paralympics-singapore-s-theresa-goh-wins-bronze-in-100m-breastst-7788098|title=Paralympics: Singapore's Theresa Goh wins bronze in 100m breaststroke SB4 final|website=Channel NewsAsia}}</ref> While qualifying for the finals, she set a new Asian record in the heats at 1:54.50.<ref name=16Para100mbreastHeats>{{cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/sports/theresa-goh-sets-new-asian-mark-en-route-reaching-breaststroke-final|title=Theresa Goh sets new Asian mark en route to reaching breaststroke final|website=TODAYonline}}</ref>\n*8 September \u2013 Plans for a new HDB town in [[Tengah, Singapore|Tengah]] are launched. It will be a town in a forest with a car-free town centre.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Kenneth |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/peek-tengah-next-new-hdb-town-size-bishan |title=A peek into Tengah, the next new HDB town the size of Bishan |website=Today |access-date=28 April 2019 |date=8 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Heng |first1=Janice |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/housing/tengah-the-first-hdb-town-since-punggol-to-have-forest-fringe-car-free-town-centre |title=Tengah, the first HDB town since Punggol, to have forest fringe, car-free town centre |website=The Straits Times |access-date=6 November 2019 |date=8 September 2016}}</ref> The first flats are launched in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Derek |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/housing/hdb-launches-over-7000-flats-for-sale-including-first-bto-project-in-tengah |title=HDB launches over 7,000 flats for sale, including first BTO project in Tengah |website=The Straits Times |access-date=6 November 2019 |date=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n*14 September \u2013 Total local Zika cases have reached 333;<ref>{{cite web|title=4 new Zika cases confirmed Monday, bringing total to 333|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/4-new-zika-cases-confirmed-monday-bringing-total-to-333/3121276.html|publisher=[[Channel News Asia]]|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref> with infected patients from previously affected areas, as well as Simei's Harvey Crescent, Upper Thomson's Tagore Avenue, Yishun Street 81,<ref>{{cite web|title=Local Zika infections jump to 151; new cases found in Tagore, Yishun, Harvey Crescent|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/local-zika-infections-jump-to-151-new-cases-found-in-tagore/3092316.html|publisher=[[Channel News Asia]]|accessdate=2 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/2016/09/tracking-zika-singapore/index.html|title=Tracking Singapore's Zika outbreak|access-date=2016-09-08}}</ref> Bishan Street 12, Elite Terrace and Ubi Crescent. A new cluster of Jalan Raya and Circuit Road formed, while Bedok North Avenue 3 formed a cluster with Bedok North Avenue 2 and Bedok North Street 3, and also the Aljunied Crescent cluster expanded to Circuit Road, Geylang East Central and Geylang East Avenue 1.<ref name=12Sep16>{{cite web|title=38 new local Zika cases confirmed Friday, bringing total to 189|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/11-new-cases-of-zika-confirmed-sunday-10-have-no-known-links-to/3118434.html|publisher=[[Channel News Asia]]|accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref>\n*15 September \u2013 [[CorpPass]] is officially launched for businesses to access secured Government transactions, which will be a requirement in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/government-economy/singapore-to-launch-corporate-digital-identity-corppass-on-sept-15|title=Singapore to launch corporate digital identity CorpPass on Sept 15|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref>\n*16 September - The [[Building and Construction Authority]] announced eight recommendations to improve lift safety after several incidents involving lifts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Heng |first1=Janice |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/bca-encourages-lift-owners-to-modernise-their-existing-lifts-for-better-reliability |title=BCA encourages lift owners to modernise their existing lifts for better reliability |website=The Straits Times |access-date=16 September 2019 |date=16 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Heng |first1=Janice |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/modernise-lifts-to-boost-safety-urges-bca |tit