e films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Most Eligible Bachelor\n| image = Most Eligible Bachelor Poster.jpeg\n| caption = First Look Poster\n| director = [[Bhaskar (director)|Bhaskar]]\n| producer = Bunny Vas<br />[[Vasu Varma]] <br />[[Allu Aravind]](Presenter) \n| writer = Bhaskar\n| starring = [[Akhil Akkineni]]<br />[[Pooja Hegde]] <br/>[[Murali Sharma]]\n| music = [[Gopi Sundar]]\n| cinematography = Pradeesh Varma\n| editing =  [[Marthand K. Venkatesh]] \n| studio = [[Geetha Arts|GA2 Pictures]]\n| released = {{Film date|2020|04}}\n| runtime = \n| country = India\n| language = Telugu\n| budget = \n| gross = \n}}\n\n'''''Most Eligible Bachelor''''' is a 2020 [[India]]n [[Telugu language|Telugu]] film written and directed by [[Bhaskar (director)|Bhaskar]] and produced by Bunny Vas and [[Vasu Varma]] on [[Geetha Arts|GA2 Pictures]] featuring [[Akhil Akkineni]], [[Pooja Hegde]] in the lead roles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://telugu.news18.com/news/movies/akhil-akkineni-new-title-most-eligible-bachelor-and-akhil-first-look-go-viral-ta-448658.html |title=\u0c28\u0c21\u0c3f\u0c30\u0c4b\u0c21\u0c4d\u0c21\u0c41\u0c2a\u0c48 \u0c1a\u0c46\u0c2a\u0c4d\u0c2a\u0c41\u0c32\u0c41 \u0c32\u0c47\u0c15\u0c41\u0c02\u0c21\u0c3e\u0c28\u0c47 \u0c05\u0c15\u0c4d\u0c15\u0c3f\u0c28\u0c47\u0c28\u0c3f \u0c35\u0c3e\u0c30\u0c41\u0c38\u0c41\u0c21\u0c41.. \u0c05\u0c2f\u0c4d\u0c2f\u0c47 \u0c07\u0c26\u0c47\u0c02 \u0c17\u0c24\u0c3f.. |date=2020-02-08 |website=News18 Telugu |publisher=[[CNN-News18]] |location=India |access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref> The music was composed by [[Gopi Sundar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/akhils-4th-film-with-bommarillu-bhaskar-launched/articleshow/69478015.cms|title=Akhil's 4th film with Bommarillu Bhaskar launched - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>. The film is scheduled to release in April 2020<ref name=\"FSP\">{{cite web|author=Geetha ArtsVerified account |url=https://twitter.com/GeethaArts/status/1226121064075292672?s=19 |title=Geetha Arts on Twitter: \"Journey of our #MostEligibleBachelor starts now with this step |publisher=Twitter.com |date=2009-11-26 |accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref>.\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development ===\nIn February 2019, story discussions took place between [[Akhil Akkineni]] and director [[Bhaskar (director)|Bhaskar]] with [[Geetha Arts|GA2 Pictures]]'s Bunny Vas attached to produce the movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/akhils-next-with-bommarillu-bhaskar-set-to-kick-off-from-summer/articleshow/68073881.cms|title=Akhil's next with Bommarillu Bhaskar set to kick-off from summer - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n=== Muhurtham (Launch) ===\nOn 24 May 2019 movie got officially launched at Filmnagar temple with Pooja. Akhil's parents [[Akkineni Nagarjuna]], [[Amala Akkineni]] along with film crew joined the occasion. It was also revealed director [[Vasu Varma]] is co producing along with Bunny Vas<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.in.com/entertainment/regional/akhil-akkinenis-will-be-working-with-bommarillu-bhaskar-for-his-next-420049.htm|title=Akhil Akkineni's will be working with Bommarillu Bhaskar for his next|first1=Bommarillu Bhaskar In com Staff-|last1=May 24|first2=2019 09:13 Pm|last2=Ist|website=in.com}}</ref>.\n\n=== Casting ===\nThe film crew auditioned over 100 actresses and models for leading actress<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehansindia.com/cinema/tollywood/akhil-team-thumb-down-100-divas-552013|title=Akhil & team thumb down 100 divas?|first=B. V. S.|last=Prakash|website=The Hans India|date=2019-08-04}}</ref>. They finalised [[Pooja Hegde]] as the lead in August 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/amp/news/movies/pooja-hegde-roped-in-to-romance-akhil-akkineni-in-bommarillu-bhaskars-next-2288219.html|title=Pooja Hegde Roped in to Romance Akhil Akkineni in Bommarillu Bhaskar's Next|website=www.news18.com}}</ref>.\n=== Filming ===\nThe filming is scheduled for July 2019. However with delay in finilising female lead, the filming is delayed. The filming started early September with all the lead actors filmed. <ref>{{Cite tweet|user=GeethaArts|number=1175040498156720129|title=Welcoming @hegdepooja on her Day 1 shoot of #Akhil4 today|author=Geetha Arts|date=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Akhil Akkineni]] as Nagaraju Pandey\n* [[Pooja Hegde]] as Vibha\n* [[Aamani]]<ref name=\"Cast\" >{{cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/akhil-akkineni-bommarillu-bhaskar-film-titled-most-eligible-bachelor-title-poster-unveiled/amp_articleshow/73936428.cms |title=Akhil Akkineni, Bommarillu Bhaskar film titled Most Eligible Bachelor; title poster unveiled &#124; Telugu Movie News - Times of India |publisher=M.timesofindia.com |date=2020-02-04 |accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n* [[Murali Sharma]] <ref name=\"Cast\" />\n* [[Vennela Kishore]] <ref name=\"Cast\" />\n* [[Jayaprakash]] <ref name=\"Cast\" />\n* [[Pragathi]] <ref name=\"Cast\" />\n* [[Amit Tiwari]]<ref name=\"Cast\" />\n* [[Eesha Rebba]]<ref>{{cite web|author=akhil pooja hegde |url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/amp/entertainment/tollywood/040220/akhils-the-most-eligible-bachelor.html |title=Akhil\u2019s the Most Eligible Bachelor |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date=2020-02-04 |accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n* Getup Srinu<ref name=\"Cast\" />\n* [[Sudigali Sudheer]]<ref name=\"Cast\" />\n* Abhay<ref name=\"Cast\" />\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Most Eligible Bachelor \n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Gopi Sundar]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 2020\n| recorded     = 2019\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = \n| language     = Telugu\n| label        = [[Aditya Music]]\n| producer     = Gopi Sundar\n| prev_title   = [[World Famous Lover]] \n| prev_year    = 2020 \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = \n{{Singles\n | name        = Most Eligible Bachelor\n | type        = Soundtrack\n | single1     = Manasa Manasa\n | single1date = {{Start date|df=yes|2020|03|02}}\n}}\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline = Track list\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = \n| title1 = Manasa Manasa\n| lyrics1 = Surendra Krishna\n| extra1 = [[Sid Sriram]] \n| length1 = 4:13\n| title2 = \n| lyrics2 = \n| extra2 = \n| length2 = \n| title3 = \n| lyrics3 = \n| extra3 = \n| length3 = \n| title4 = \n| lyrics4 =\n| extra4 = \n| length4 = \n| title5 = \n| lyrics5 = \n| extra5 = \n| length5 = \n}}\n\n== Release ==\nThe film is scheduled to be released in April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moviesreviewcast.com/2020/02/most-eligible-bachelor-movie.html|title=Most Eligible Bachelor Movie Release Date, Latest News,Shooting, Trailer, Cast, Poster|publisher=Moviesreviewcast.com|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Promotion ===\nThe title was revealed on 4 February 2020 announcing the first look release date.<ref>{{cite web|author=Geetha ArtsVerified account |url=https://twitter.com/GeethaArts/status/1224659971595358209?s=19 |title=Geetha Arts on Twitter: \"Introducing our MOST ELIGIBLE BACHELOR @AkhilAkkineni8|publisher=Twitter.com |date=2020-02-04 |accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{IMDb title|11725680}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Most Eligible Bachelor}} \n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:2020s Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian thriller films]]\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in India]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Telangana]]\n[[Category:Upcoming Telugu-language films]]\n", "name_user": "Bovineboy2008", "label": "safe", "comment": "release postponed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Most_Eligible_Bachelor_(2020_film)"}
{"title_page": "Bobby Thompson (comedian)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Bobby Thompson\n| birth_name               = Robert Michael Thompson\n| birth_date               = {{Birth date|1911|11|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place              = [[Penshaw]], [[Sunderland]], England\n| death_date               = {{Death date and age|1988|04|16|1911|11|18|df=y}}\n| death_place              = [[North Shields]], [[Tyne and Wear]], England\n| occupation              = Comedian\n| spouse                  = Eleanor Cicely Palmer\n| children                =\n| parents                 = John and Mary Thompson\n}}\n\n'''Robert Michael \"Bobby\" Thompson''' (18 November 1911 \u2013 16 April 1988) was a stand-up comedian, actor and entertainer from [[Penshaw]], [[Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaysun.co.uk/tm_headline=&method=full&objectid=18543148&siteid=50081-name_page.html|title=Bobby Thompson|date=2007|publisher=Sunday Sun|accessdate=2009-04-25}}</ref> Although he was raised in [[Penshaw]], he also lived in [[Great Lumley]] and [[Barley Mow]], near [[Chester-le-Street]], later moving to [[Whitley Bay]].<ref name=\"echoresearch\">{{cite news |title=Bobby Thompson marks 50 years as entertainer |date=16 February 1976 |newspaper=Sunderland Echo |page=2}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nHe was the seventh child of John and Mary Thompson, both of whom died by the time Bobby was eight years old. He was then raised by his elder sister in the village of [[Fatfield]].\n\nAfter leaving school at fifteen, he started worked at North Biddick Colliery, earning seven shillings and sixpence a week. He would supplement his income by playing the [[harmonica]] around local [[working men's club]]s and competing in [[domino]] tournaments. His first stand-up performance took place at the Gem Cinema in Penshaw as a young boy.\n\nThompson was married three times. His second wife, Phyllis, died on 25 April 1967. He announced his engagement to Mary Douglass, 62, of [[Annfield Plain]] a few years later, but the engagement was called off. In 1980, Thompson married his housekeeper, Eleanor Cicely Palmer, more commonly known as Cissy Ward (n\u00e9e Wake). Thompson was her third husband and she was famous for being taller than him.\n\n==Career==\nFamous for his broad [[Pitmatic]] ([[County Durham]] pit village) accent (often mistaken for [[Geordie]]), self-deprecating humour and mastery of the mother-in-law joke, Thompson was affectionately known as ''The Little Waster'' due to his short stature, which he often played on during his act, describing himself as 'Little Bobby'. His most famous outfit was a worn out stripey jumper (Wooly gansey) and [[flat cap]]. His ever-present [[Woodbine (cigarette)|Woodbine]] [[cigarette]] stub, hanging from the corner of his mouth, was also an integral part of his on-stage persona.\n\nHis attempts to move beyond [[North East England]] were limited by his accent and the regional bias of his humour, although he did enjoy some success with the [[BBC]] show, ''Wot Cheor Geordie''.\n\nHe was also renowned for his problems with the tax man, stemming from the fact that he never seemed to pay any. This was an unfortunate fact that he turned to humour in his stage act.\n\nBobby made recordings of three comedy songs written for him by local composer [[Eric Boswell (songwriter)|Eric Boswell]]: ''You Little Waster'', ''The Golden Voice of Bobby'' and ''When I Was A Lad''. The songs incorporated jokes from Bobby's act and ''When I Was A Lad'' was even released as a single locally.\n\nProblems with drink, finances and his health affected his career in the 1970s, but he remained a North East favourite, particularly on the club scene, until shortly before his death.\n\n==Quotes==\n*\"The dole is my shepherd, I shall not work.\"\n*\"She shouts from upstairs, Bobby can yer fix the string on wa carrier . . . why am nae.\"\n*\"I'll give ya a bottle o' Brandy if you can tell us you pay the 'lectric bill before you get the red tooth.\"\n*\"A man come to ou door. I said come in, take a seat. He says 'I'm coming in to take the lot.'\"\n*\"Wu got off the at Blackpool, the porter came up an' asked if 'e could carry. I said 'Na, let 'er'.\"\n*\"Wu went into the restaurant an' asked for a coffee. The waiter asked if wu wanted black or white. She says 'I'll have black wi' milk in'.\"\n*On the night of the 1951 election when the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] was rumoured to be planning to abolish the [[National Health Service]]: \"It came tu last orders and the barman shouted 'Come on, let's see yer glasses off', and I said 'Well, them Tories haven't wasted any time, have the!'\"\n*\"You believe Bobby Thompson. If yu pays what yu owe yu'll never have [[Gout]].\"\n*\"When ya drunk, yu say things yu don't mean. I says to her I love ya. After a wiped the faeces off me face&nbsp;... A says gis a kiss under the mistletoe. She says aks me mother'. I wish a could've found an axe. Aks 'er mother for a kiss under the mistletoe, a wouldn' kiss 'er under chloroform!\"\n*\"1939 - I was secretary for the street&nbsp;... I went for treasurer but a was too well known!\"\n*\"She's putting up sandwiches on the Monday an' wa not gannin till the Wednesday. Well ye kna tinned tomatoes torn claggy\"\n*\"They came into the court and they woz givin' the papers out to the jurerors ([[Jury]])&nbsp;... She shouts 'Bobby, there must be a [[Housie]] on before the case!'\"\n*\"The judge said 'You owe seven pence, can you pay?'... I said 'yes your honour'\"\n*\"Noo, Ah divvent kna where aal ye's are from&nbsp;... (changes to a German accent) but I'm from Shank House.\"\n*\"She says 'Bobby, we'll just have a two course lunch cos its rather'. Two course?! Chips n' sauce!!\"\n*\"There was a knock at oor door last Wednesday mornin'. He says, 'Am from [[Littlewoods]]', I says, 'God bless ya! I've won the treble chance?!' He says, \"Nah, your wife's up for defecating in the shoe section!\"\n*\"Now, that's the thing aboot debt. Some calls it debt, ya see, and then there's them what calls it credit. Committee mens' wives, 'on account'. Well, am in debt on account of not being able to pay me credit!\"\n*\"Ah went to the doctors. He said, \"Can you walk?\". Ah said, \"Work! ah can't even waak!\"\n*\"The Queen came up tiv us with a plate of cakes. \"Bobby, would you like a scone or a meringue?\". Ah says, \"Nah ya quite right, ah'll have a scone\"\n\n== Death ==\nThompson died on 16 April 1988, after suffering from emphysema and cancer.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/7014115.little-wasters-son-is-branded-drunken-nuisance/ | title=Little Waster's son is branded drunken nuisance | date=29 September 2003 | newspaper=The Northern Echo | accessdate=29 December 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/bobbys-real-life-tragedy-1679260 | title=Bobby's real life tragedy | date=29 March 2001 | newspaper=Evening Chronicle | accessdate=29 December 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/bobby-thompsons-son-speaks-dad-2635643 | title=Bobby Thompson's son speaks about dad on the 25th anniversary of his death | date=16 April 2013 | first=Kate | last=Proctor | publisher=Chronicle Live | accessdate=29 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://frankwappat.com/bobby-thompson.html North East Comedian Bobby Thompson]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Bobby}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:People from Sunderland, Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:20th-century comedians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Bobby Thompson\n| birth_name               = Robert Michael Thompson\n| birth_date               = {{Birth date|1911|11|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place              = [[Penshaw]], [[Sunderland]], England\n| death_date               = {{Death date and age|1988|04|16|1911|11|18|df=y}}\n| death_place              = [[North Shields]], [[Tyne and Wear]], England\n| occupation              = Comedian\n| spouse                  = Eleanor Cicely Palmer\n| children                =\n| parents                 = John and Mary Thompson\n}}\n\n'''Robert Michael \"Bobby\" Thompson''' (18 November 1911 \u2013 16 April 1988) was a stand-up comedian, actor and entertainer from [[Penshaw]], [[Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaysun.co.uk/tm_headline=&method=full&objectid=18543148&siteid=50081-name_page.html|title=Bobby Thompson|date=2007|publisher=Sunday Sun|accessdate=2009-04-25}}</ref> Although he was raised in [[Penshaw]], he also lived in [[Great Lumley]] and [[Barley Mow]], near [[Chester-le-Street]], later moving to [[Whitley Bay]].<ref name=\"echoresearch\">{{cite news |title=Bobby Thompson marks 50 years as entertainer |date=16 February 1976 |newspaper=Sunderland Echo |page=2}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nHe was the seventh child of John and Mary Thompson, both of whom died by the time Bobby was eight years old. He was then raised by his elder sister in the village of [[Fatfield]].\n\nAfter leaving school at fifteen, he started worked at North Biddick Colliery, earning seven shillings and sixpence a week. He would supplement his income by playing the [[harmonica]] around local [[working men's club]]s and competing in [[domino]] tournaments. His first stand-up performance took place at the Gem Cinema in Penshaw as a young boy.\n\nThompson was married three times. His second wife, Phyllis, died on 25 April 1967. He announced his engagement to Mary Douglass, 62, of [[Annfield Plain]] a few years later, but the engagement was called off. In 1980, Thompson married his housekeeper, Eleanor Cicely Palmer, more commonly known as Cissy Ward (n\u00e9e Wake). Thompson was her third husband and she was famous for being taller than him.\n\n==Career==\nFamous for his broad [[Pitmatic]] ([[County Durham]] pit village) accent (often mistaken for [[Geordie]]), self-deprecating humour and mastery of the mother-in-law joke, Thompson was affectionately known as ''The Little Waster'' due to his short stature, which he often played on during his act, describing himself as 'Little Bobby'. His most famous outfit was a worn out stripey jumper (Wooly gansey) and [[flat cap]]. His ever-present [[Woodbine (cigarette)|Woodbine]] [[cigarette]] stub, hanging from the corner of his mouth, was also an integral part of his on-stage persona.\n\nHis attempts to move beyond [[North East England]] were limited by his accent and the regional bias of his humour, although he did enjoy some success with the [[BBC]] show, ''Wot Cheor Geordie''.\n\nHe was also renowned for his problems with the tax man, stemming from the fact that he never seemed to pay any. This was an unfortunate fact that he turned to humour in his stage act.\n\nBobby made recordings of three comedy songs written for him by local composer [[Eric Boswell (songwriter)|Eric Boswell]]: ''You Little Waster'', ''The Golden Voice of Bobby'' and ''When I Was A Lad''. The songs incorporated jokes from Bobby's act and ''When I Was A Lad'' was even released as a single locally.\n\nProblems with drink, finances and his health affected his career in the 1970s, but he remained a North East favourite, particularly on the club scene, until shortly before his death.\n\n==Quotes==\n*\"The dole is my shepherd, I shall not work.\"\n*\"She shouts from upstairs, Bobby can yer fix the string on wa carrier . . . why am nae.\"\n*\"I'll give ya a bottle o' Brandy if you can tell us you pay the 'lectric bill before you get the red tooth.\"\n*\"A man come to ou door. I said come in, take a seat. He says 'I'm coming in to take the lot.'\"\n*\"Wu got off the at Blackpool, the porter came up an' asked if 'e could carry. I said 'Na, let 'er'.\"\n*\"Wu went into the restaurant an' asked for a coffee. The waiter asked if wu wanted black or white. She says 'I'll have black wi' milk in'.\"\n*On the night of the 1951 election when the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] was rumoured to be planning to abolish the [[National Health Service]]: \"It came tu last orders and the barman shouted 'Come on, let's see yer glasses off', and I said 'Well, them Tories haven't wasted any time, have the!'\"\n*\"You believe Bobby Thompson. If yu pays what yu owe yu'll never have [[Gout]].\"\n*\"When ya drunk, yu say things yu don't mean. I says to her I love ya. After a wiped the faeces off me face&nbsp;... A says gis a kiss under the mistletoe. She says aks me mother'. I wish a could've found an axe. Aks 'er mother for a kiss under the mistletoe, a wouldn' kiss 'er under chloroform!\"\n*\"1939 - I was secretary for the street&nbsp;... I went for treasurer but a was too well known!\"\n*\"She's putting up sandwiches on the Monday an' wa not gannin till the Wednesday. Well ye kna tinned tomatoes torn claggy\"\n*\"They came into the court and they woz givin' the papers out to the jurerors ([[Jury]])&nbsp;... She shouts 'Bobby, there must be a [[Housie]] on before the case!'\"\n*\"The judge said 'You owe seven pence, can you pay?'... I said 'yes your honour'\"\n*\"Noo, Ah divvent kna where aal ye's are from&nbsp;... (changes to a German accent) but I'm from Shank House.\"\n*\"She says 'Bobby, we'll just have a two course lunch cos its rather'. Two course?! Chips n' sauce!!\"\n*\"There was a knock at oor door last Wednesday mornin'. He says, 'Am from [[Littlewoods]]', I says, 'God bless ya! I've won the treble chance?!' He says, \"Nah, your wife's up for defecating in the shoe section!\"\n*\"Now, that's the thing aboot debt. Some calls it debt, ya see, and then there's them what calls it credit. Committee mens' wives, 'on account'. Well, am in debt on account of not being able to pay me credit!\"\n*\"Ah went to the doctors. He said, \"Can you walk?\". Ah said, \"Work! ah can't even waak!\"\n*\"The Queen came up tiv us with a plate of cakes. \"Bobby, would you like a  or a?\". Ah says, \"Nah ya quite right, ah'll have a scone\"\n\n== Death ==\nThompson died on 16 April 1988, after suffering from emphysema and cancer.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/7014115.little-wasters-son-is-branded-drunken-nuisance/ | title=Little Waster's son is branded drunken nuisance | date=29 September 2003 | newspaper=The Northern Echo | accessdate=29 December 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/bobbys-real-life-tragedy-1679260 | title=Bobby's real life tragedy | date=29 March 2001 | newspaper=Evening Chronicle | accessdate=29 December 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/bobby-thompsons-son-speaks-dad-2635643 | title=Bobby Thompson's son speaks about dad on the 25th anniversary of his death | date=16 April 2013 | first=Kate | last=Proctor | publisher=Chronicle Live | accessdate=29 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://frankwappat.com/bobby-thompson.html North East Comedian Bobby Thompson]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Bobby}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:People from Sunderland, Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:20th-century comedians]]\n", "name_user": "Ian Gardhouse", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eQuotes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobby_Thompson_(comedian)"}
